 person. Compare   Lo Bosco  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Boschetti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Angelina, Antonio, Guido, Rosario.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Bosco  ."]},{"name":"Lo Bosco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Gennaro, Sal, Salvatore, Antonino, Nichola, Pasquale, Piera, Raffaela, Rocco.","Italian (southern; also <b>Lobosco</b>): variant of   Bosco  , with the addition of the definite article <i>lo</i>."]}]},{"name":"Agnese","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Agnes</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnese del Bosco was born as the daughter of Marchese Guglielmo IV del Bosco. She had at least 4 sons and 2 daughters with Marchese Federico Malaspina di Villafranca. She died about 1260, in Europe."},"et":{"–aproximadamente 1260":"–umbes 1260","–1260":"–1260","–1264":"–1264","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1200–1294":"1200–1294","–1301":"–1301","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–1250":"–1250","aproximadamente 1130":"umbes 1130","aproximadamente 1260":"umbes 1260","1301":"1301","da 1200 a 1220":"1200 kuni 1220","aproximadamente 